ering a fascinating account of small state diplomacy, and a unique perspective on African decolonisation, this book provides essential insight for scholars of Irish history, African history, international relations, and the history of NGOs, as well as anyone interested in Africa’s important place in the Irish public imagination.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 4amanchesterhive variable pricing textbooks. 7aHISTORY / Europe / Great Britain / General.2bisacsh  aAfrica.  aAnti-apartheid movement.  aCold War.  aDecolonisation.  aForeign aid.  aInternational relations.  aIreland.  aNon-governmental organisations.  aState identity.  aUnited Nations.1 aO’Sullivan, Kevin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 1986 - 2013 eBook Packagez9783111283630oZDB-23-MUP40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781526130549423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781526130549/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-MUPc1986d2013